<h3>About the Website</h3>
<p>
  Who is your State Senator?
</p>
<p>
  I’ll betcha don’t know.
</p>
<p>
  When I realized that I didn't know who mine was, I was kind of surprised. You see, I’m a fairly engaged citizen and have been politically for over 15 years. I am engaged enough to follow news from multiple sources just to make sure I hear from all sides of the story. 
</p>
<p>
  But, I didn't even know who my local State Senator was and I wanted to understand why. 
</p>
<p>
  One reason is that the vast majority of news from major sources is focused on national issues, not state and local. However, the things that impact me most in terms of day-to-day life are local. 
</p>
<p>
  That seems a bit backwards to me.
</p>
<p>
  ----
</p>
<p>
  Another thing that seems broken in our current system is the ratio of signal to noise in the information we consume. 
</p>
<p>
  In the era of 24/7 news sensationalism is more important than truth. "News" devolves into pundits from opposite ends of the political spectrum yelling at each other to create tension and elicit emotional responses from viewers. 
</p>
<p>
  It really is just entertainment under the guise of news. I don't think "Fake News" is a thing in a literal sense, but you'd have to be pretty naieve to not understand why the phrase stuck. 
</p>
<p>
  ----
</p>
<p>
  Wanting to reduce the signal-to-noise ratio, I thought: "Why not just go straight to the source?" In this case, the "source" is the set of people who represent you in governemnt. Figuring out who those people are is the first step in changing the government.
</p>
<p>
